const CASES=[
  {title:"Case 1: Devon",subtitle:"New Client — DOMS, Frequency & Double-Progression",
   scenario:`Devon, 30M, no structured exercise in 5 years. Goals: get stronger and build muscle. Wants to train 5 days/week immediately. Full commercial gym access.

Assessment: Healthy, BMI 26. Movement screen: mild anterior pelvic tilt, limited hip mobility. No barbell experience.

After Session 1 (3×8 squats, lunges, rows — moderate weight), Devon calls 2 days later: "I can barely walk — my legs are on fire. I think I'm injured."`,
   questions:`1) Is Devon's experience normal? Explain the physiological mechanism.
2) Should Devon train 5 days/week? Design appropriate frequency using Chapter 9 evidence.
3) Design his initial 4-week program addressing strength/hypertrophy goals AND movement screen findings.
4) Explain the double-progression protocol to Devon in plain language — apply it to his squat.`,
   answer:`1) NORMAL DOMS — NOT INJURY:
Devon has DOMS (Delayed Onset Muscle Soreness).
• Mechanism: Eccentric actions (lowering phases of squat/lunge) cause microscopic muscle fiber microtrauma
• Timing: Peaks 24–72 hours post-exercise = classic DOMS (Devon's call = day 2 = expected)
• First session = most severe: untrained muscles have no protective adaptation yet
• Tell Devon: "This is muscles adapting — a positive sign, NOT injury. Reduces significantly by session 3–4."
• Management: Light walking, gentle movement; complete rest actually slows clearance of metabolic waste

2) 5 DAYS/WEEK = INAPPROPRIATE FOR BEGINNER:
• Research: 2–3 days/week produces significantly greater lean mass gains than 1 day/week for new exercisers
• Advanced exercisers need ~72 hours recovery between sessions targeting same muscle group
• Devon's status: Untrained → needs 72 hr minimum recovery; excessive frequency → excessive DOMS → dropout
• RECOMMENDATION: 3 days/week full-body (Mon/Wed/Fri) for weeks 1–4
• Each muscle group trained 3× per week with 48–72 hr between sessions
• Progress to 4-day split after 6–8 weeks when base conditioning established

3) 4-WEEK PROGRAM:
Movement screen: Anterior pelvic tilt → core stability priority; Limited hip mobility → hip prep before loading

Warm-up (10 min): 90/90 hip stretches, glute bridges, bird dogs, dead bugs (address pelvic tilt + hip mobility)

Strength Block (3 days/week):
• Goblet squat 3×10 (learn pattern safely; core + leg development)
• Dumbbell RDL 3×10 (hip hinge pattern; posterior chain → reduces anterior tilt)
• Dumbbell chest press 3×10 (upper push; controlled)
• Dumbbell row 3×10 (upper pull; postural balance)
• Plank 3×30 sec (core stability, spinal support)
Exercise order: Large/compound first (squat, RDL, press, row); core isolation last.
Volume: Conservative 3×10 — allows neural adaptation without excessive DOMS
Weeks 1–2: Technique focus (RPE 6–7); Weeks 3–4: Apply double-progression (RPE 7–8)

4) DOUBLE-PROGRESSION EXPLAINED:
"Devon — here's how we add weight safely:
Pick a range: 8 to 12 reps on goblet squat with 20 kg.
Step 1 (ADD REPS): If you manage 8 reps today, next session go for 9, then 10, 11, 12. Same weight throughout.
Step 2 (ADD WEIGHT): Once you hit 12 clean reps, increase weight ~5% (20 → 21 kg). Now start over from 8 reps.
No time limit — it might take 1 week or 4 weeks. Weight increases ONLY when you earn it with good form. No guessing, no ego — just systematic progress."`
  },
  {title:"Case 2: Amara",subtitle:"Strength Plateau — Diminishing Returns + Specificity",
   scenario:`Amara, 28F, 3 years consistent training, 4 days/week upper/lower split. Bench press stuck at 65 kg for 4 months. Eats well, sleeps enough, trains hard.

Problem: Exclusively uses barbell bench press for chest pressing. Program unchanged for 6 months. Technique is good. Uses 3×5 with 3-min rest intervals.`,
   questions:`1) Identify the principle explaining Amara's plateau. What does it predict at her level?
2) How does the specificity principle BOTH help AND limit her bench press progress?
3) Design a 6-week modification to break her plateau — include 3 specific changes with physiological rationale.
4) Amara asks: "Should I just add more sets and reps?" — Explain volume vs. intensity trade-offs at her level.`,
   answer:`1) PRINCIPLE: DIMINISHING RETURNS
• Definition: As fitness level increases, progressively greater effort required for smaller additional gains
• At Amara's level (3 years, 65 kg bench): neural and structural adaptations largely exhausted by current stimulus
• Prediction: A gain that took 2 weeks as a beginner may now take months of targeted specialization
• Contributing factor: Same stimulus for 6 months = body fully adapted = no new signal for further adaptation

2) SPECIFICITY — HELPS AND LIMITS:
HELPS: 3 years of barbell bench = highly specific neural pattern → excellent motor unit recruitment for that exact movement. Her technique is good because SAID adaptations are maximal for barbell bench mechanics.
LIMITS: Body is maximally adapted to this specific stimulus → no new adaptation signal available. Same movement = same demand = same result. Adjacent movements (dumbbell press, incline) recruit chest muscles at slightly different angles/ranges → new neuromuscular stimulus.

3) 6-WEEK PLATEAU-BREAKING MODIFICATIONS:
A) Primary Press Rotation:
• Weeks 1–3: Dumbbell bench press 4×6–8
• Weeks 4–6: Incline barbell press 4×5–6
• Rationale: Dumbbell = increased ROM + independent arm stabilization = new muscle activation demands. Incline = different angle → upper pec/anterior delt stimulus. New neuromuscular patterns = renewed adaptation.

B) Eccentric Tempo Manipulation:
• Add 3-sec eccentric on all pressing movements
• Rationale: Eccentric overload creates different mechanical stress → new hypertrophic/neural stimulus in Type IIa/IIx fibers. Amara likely rushing the lowering phase — controlled eccentric = greater time under tension.

C) Antagonist Strengthening:
• Add cable rows + face pulls (3×12) targeting rhomboids, rear deltoids
• Rationale: 3 years of pressing priority = potential anterior shoulder dominance. Stronger antagonists improve shoulder stability = better force transfer during pressing movements. Specificity: antagonist strength directly affects agonist performance.

4) VOLUME vs. INTENSITY AT AMARA'S LEVEL:
"More sets/reps alone won't break Amara's plateau.
• Volume approach: Works for hypertrophy and beginners. But adding MORE volume to a stale movement = more fatigue, same stimulus, no new adaptation.
• Intensity approach: Amara is already at max for current stimulus — she can't simply add weight (that IS the plateau).
• REAL ANSWER: Change the STIMULUS first. Specificity = body adapts to exact demands. Different demand = new adaptation period. After 6 weeks of variation → return to barbell bench → neural pattern refreshed → likely PR.
Advanced athletes periodize for this reason: systematically vary exercise, volume, AND intensity to always present a new adaptation signal."`
  },
  {title:"Case 3: Grace",subtitle:"'I Don't Want to Bulk Up' — Hypertrophy Factors",
   scenario:`Grace, 45F, teacher, wants to "tone up" and improve strength for daily activities. Nervous about lifting: "My friend does weights and she got huge. I don't want to look like a bodybuilder."

No training experience. BMI 24, healthy. Daily life: carrying groceries, climbing stairs, picking up grandchildren.`,
   questions:`1) Address Grace's fear using ≥4 physiological factors that influence hypertrophy potential.
2) Design her program using the needs assessment framework based on her daily life activities.
3) Which type of hypertrophy (myofibrillar vs. sarcoplasmic) is relevant to Grace's goals — and why?
4) Grace asks: "What rep range should I use?" Explain based on her specific goals.`,
   answer:`1) ADDRESSING GRACE'S FEAR — 4 HYPERTROPHY FACTORS:
A) HORMONE LEVELS (most important): Females produce ~10–20× less testosterone than males. Testosterone is the primary anabolic hormone driving significant muscle hypertrophy. Without high testosterone, large muscle mass gains are physiologically very difficult. Competitive female bodybuilders achieve their physique through years of extreme specialization + specific nutritional protocols — not from a 3×/week beginner program.

B) SEX: Directly linked to hormonal profile. Women's hormonal environment limits hypertrophic potential relative to men. Women CAN gain significant functional strength through neural adaptations without visible size increases.

C) AGE (Grace is 45): Anabolic hormone production (testosterone, growth hormone) declines with age. This makes significant hypertrophy MORE difficult for Grace, not easier. Primary adaptations will be neural efficiency + modest functional strength — not bulk.

D) MUSCLE FIBER TYPE: Large bodybuilder hypertrophy requires high percentage of Type II (fast-twitch) fibers. Grace's ADLs (standing, carrying) predominantly use Type I (endurance) fibers. Her likely Type I-dominant composition = lower hypertrophy ceiling.
CONCLUSION: "You will get stronger and more capable — you will NOT accidentally become a bodybuilder."

2) NEEDS ASSESSMENT FOR GRACE:
Movement Analysis (ADLs):
• Carrying groceries → loaded carry, grip strength, single-leg stability
• Climbing stairs → single-leg squat pattern, hip extension
• Picking up grandchildren → hip hinge, spinal stability
Physiological Parameters: Functional strength + muscular endurance (standing all day); NOT maximal strength or size

PROGRAM (3×/week, full-body):
Warm-up: glute bridges, hip circles, band walks
• Goblet squat 3×12 (sitting/rising, object pickup)
• Dumbbell Romanian deadlift 3×12 (lifting from floor, posterior chain)
• Single-leg step-up 3×10 each (stair climbing, balance)
• Farmer's carry 3×30 sec (grocery carrying — loaded bilateral)
• Dumbbell row 3×12 (pulling, postural balance vs. teacher forward lean)
• Plank 3×30 sec (core stability for all carrying/lifting)
Exercise order: Compound/large first; core last. Progressive overload via double-progression.

3) HYPERTROPHY TYPE FOR GRACE:
MYOFIBRILLAR is relevant.
• Myofibrillar = growth of contractile proteins → increased FORCE PRODUCTION
• Grace needs functional strength (lift grandchildren, carry groceries) = FORCE = myofibrillar
• Result: Muscles become stronger and slightly denser — NOT visually bulky
Sarcoplasmic (NOT Grace's goal):
• Sarcoplasmic = size without force = bodybuilder aesthetic target
• Requires high volume + short rest + metabolic stress = opposite of Grace's program design
• Grace naturally avoids this stimulus with compound movements + moderate reps + adequate rest

4) REP RANGE FOR GRACE'S GOALS:
• Functional strength: 8–12 reps (Type I + IIa fibers; moderate load; adequate strength stimulus)
• Muscular endurance (teacher standing all day): 12–20 reps (trains fatigue resistance for prolonged activity)
• RECOMMENDATION: 10–15 reps — best of both worlds
• Rest: 60–90 seconds (functional + endurance balance)
• Apply double-progression: start where comfortable, add reps first, then weight in 5% steps
• Most important: consistency + progressive overload applied safely matters more than exact rep number"`
  },
